actions.comment:
Thanks for the detailed report and SVG output.

The closing `</svg>` tag is written by the underlying Skia SVG device when the canvas is disposed (destroyed). In your code, `using var canvas` defers disposal to the end of the enclosing scope — so `managedStream.ToArray()` reads the stream *before* the canvas has been disposed, and the closing tag hasn't been written yet.

Here's a workaround — use a block-scoped `using` so the canvas is disposed before you read the stream:

```csharp
using var managedStream = new MemoryStream();
using var stream = new SKManagedWStream(managedStream);

using (var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(bounds, stream))
{
    // ... draw operations ...
    canvas.DrawMeasurement(skiaRenderer, filename, file, CanvasSize, CanvasSize);
}

// Read AFTER canvas disposal — closing </svg> tag is now written
result.Data = managedStream.ToArray();
```

This matches the pattern in our own tests ([`SvgCanvasSavesFile`](https://github.com/mono/SkiaSharp/blob/main/tests/Tests/SkiaSharp/SKCanvasTest.cs#L429)). The `SKFileWStream` variant appeared to work because file I/O timing differs, but the same disposal ordering requirement applies.

This isn't a regression — the behavior has been consistent across versions. The `using var` vs `using (var ...)` scoping difference is a common C# pitfall when disposal ordering matters.
